{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}} Since 1973, the '''[[New York Yankees]]''' [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) club has enforced an '''appearance policy''' regulating how their players must be presented. It states that players must have their hair cut above the collar of their [[baseball jersey]] and no beards are permitted. The policy has raised some controversy and there have been calls for its abolition.{{Citation needed|date=May 2018}}
== History == The policy was started in 1973 by former club owner [[George Steinbrenner]], reportedly after seeing several players' hair covering their numbers during performance of the "[[Star Spangled Banner]]" and noting down their numbers (as he did not know their names) to instruct them to cut their hair. As a result, he introduced an appearance policy for the Yankees.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bashe|first=Philip|title=Dog Days: The New York Yankees' Fall from Grace and Return to Glory, 1964–1976|location=New York|publisher=Random House, Inc.|year=1994}}</ref> The official policy states "All players, coaches and male executives are forbidden to display any facial hair other than mustaches (except for religious reasons), and scalp hair may not be grown below the collar. Long sideburns and 'mutton chops' are not specifically banned."<ref>{{cite news|last=Hoch|first=Bryan|title=No beard in the Bronx: Wilson won't shave for Yanks|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/63902080/|publisher=[[Major League Baseball Advanced Media]]|date=November 13, 2013|accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdcwire.com/boston-police-departments-grooming-policies-would-make-george-steinbrenner-proud/ |title=Boston Police Department's Grooming Policies Would Make George Steinbrenner Proud |publisher=BDC Wire |date= |accessdate=August 7, 2016}}</ref> This was because Steinbrenner wanted the Yankees to adopt a corporate attitude.<ref name=wsj>{{cite web|last=Barbarisi |first=Daniel |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324048904578320741510151474 |title=Yankees: No Beards—And That's Final |work=Wall Street Journal |date=February 23, 2013 |accessdate=August 7, 2016}}</ref> The appearance policy may have been inspired by Steinbrenner's veteran status with the [[United States Air Force]], which like other military branches also has a [[Uniforms of the United States Armed Forces|similar appearance policy.]]
The policy raised some objections from the team. [[Don Mattingly]] openly defied the Yankees' management's requests for him to cut his hair. In response they removed him from the starting lineup and fined him repeatedly until he promised to trim it.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lee |first=Joon |url=http://www.hardballtimes.com/tht-live/20th-anniversary-of-don-mattinglys-hair-related-benching/ |title=20th anniversary of Don Mattingly’s hair-related benching |work=Hardball Times |date=August 15, 2011 |accessdate=August 7, 2016}}</ref> An incident that had mirrored a story in ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode "[[Homer at the Bat]]" where Mattingly was a guest star and was benched in the episode for having long sideburns (that only [[Mr. Burns]], the team manager, could see) was written months before the Yankees incident.<ref>{{cite web|last=Leitch |first=Will |url=http://nymag.com/daily/sports/2011/08/mattingly-hair-20-years-ago.html |title=Twenty Years Ago, Donnie Baseball Cut His Hair |work=NY Mag |date= |accessdate=August 7, 2016}}</ref> [[Lou Piniella]] challenged the rule during [[spring training]] in [[Fort Lauderdale]], citing that [[Jesus]] had long hair. Steinbrenner responded to this request for exemption by pointing at the nearby swimming pool and saying "[[Jesus walking on water|If you can walk on water]], you can wear your hair any way you want."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/gameon/post/2009/09/68498215/1#.V6WekzFzXIU |title=Steinbrenner, Piniella and the great Jesus debate |work=USA Today |date=September 1, 2009 |accessdate=August 7, 2016}}</ref>
The policy has become a prominent symbol of the New York Yankees.<ref name=kj /> An example of the symbolic clean-shaven look came when [[Johnny Damon]] cut his "caveman" hair and beard when joining the Yankees from the [[Boston Red Sox]] with Steinbrenner commenting "he looks like a Yankee, sounds like a Yankee, he is a Yankee".<ref name=kj>{{cite web|author=Kenny DeJohn |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1536907-its-time-for-the-new-york-yankees-to-modernize-their-facial-hair-policy |title=It's Time for the New York Yankees to Modernize Their Facial Hair Policy |work=Bleacher Report |date=February 20, 2013 |accessdate=August 7, 2016}}</ref> This policy has led to media speculation that when a player cuts his hair, he is going to sign with the Yankees. One example of this was [[San Francisco Giants]]' [[Tim Lincecum]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Kevin Kaduk |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/mlb-big-league-stew/tim-lincecum-hair-no-longer-very-long-182554604--mlb.html |title=Tim Lincecum’s hair is no longer very long |publisher=Sports.yahoo.com |date=December 20, 2012 |accessdate=August 7, 2016}}</ref> Some players, such as [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]], have openly stated that they would never join the Yankees as long as the policy was in place.<ref name=wsj />
== Calls for abolition == There have been several calls for the New York Yankees to drop the policy.{{fact|date=August 2016}} The New York Yankees players themselves skirted around the policy in 2015 by adopting the practice of growing moustaches in line with the wording of the policy.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jimmy Traina |url=http://www.foxsports.com/buzzer/photos/new-york-yankees-mustaches-050715 |title=No beards allowed for New York Yankees, so mustache madness hits the Bronx |publisher=FOX Sports |date=May 7, 2015 |accessdate=August 7, 2016}}</ref> Manager [[Joe Girardi]] stated that he would join the players if they won 10 in a row.<ref>{{cite web|last=Feinsand |first=Mark |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/yankees/mustache-craze-grows-yankees-clubhouse-article-1.2211880 |title=Mustache craze grows in Yankees clubhouse |work=NY Daily News |date=May 5, 2015 |accessdate=August 7, 2016}}</ref> This was despite Girardi stating that he would continue Steinbrenner's policy after Steinbrenner had died.<ref name=wsj />
== Other clubs == Other baseball clubs also had an appearance policy. Until 1972, there were no MLB players that had facial hair due to fashion dictates at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reds.enquirer.com/1999/02/13/red_reds_clean-shaven.html |title=Reds clean-shaven since 1902 |work=Cincinnati Enquirer |date=February 13, 1999 |accessdate=August 7, 2016}}</ref> The [[Cincinnati Reds]] had a policy against beards as an [[unwritten rule]] until 1999.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/reds-ban-on-facial-hair-lifted/ |title=Reds' Ban On Facial Hair Lifted |publisher=CBS News |date=February 16, 1999 |accessdate=August 7, 2016}}</ref> In 2016, when Mattingly became the [[field manager]] of the [[Miami Marlins]], he introduced a complete ban on any facial hair on any players.<ref>{{cite web|last=Perry |first=Dayn |url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/news/the-marlins-have-banned-facial-hair/ |title=The Marlins have banned facial hair |publisher=CBS Sports |date=February 21, 2016 |accessdate=August 7, 2016}}</ref> In 2017, the policy was abolished.{{Citation needed|date=May 2018}}
